{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dfc35a0e-7e45-4a16-bcfa-05f974f959f6","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current repository. Here's the general guidance from my knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Check for macOS crash reports** — macOS automatically captures crash logs in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps via `ulimit`** before running the app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   /path/to/your-app\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS writes core dumps there by default (if SIP allows it and the limit is set).\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your-app -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Use `bt` for a backtrace, `register read`, etc.\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty**, System Integrity Protection (SIP) may be blocking core dumps. You can check with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT crash reports won't have managed stack traces by default. Publishing with `<StripSymbols>false</StripSymbols>` and keeping the `.dsym` bundle alongside the binary will give you better native symbolication in `lldb`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39d3ffa7-35e3-4221-bb4f-a1d285341751","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository appears to be empty or has no relevant documentation about crash dumps on macOS. Let me answer from my own knowledge about recovering crash dumps on macOS for NativeAOT apps without `createdump`.","outputTokens":428,"requestId":"CB02:2BF54B:1F7CAD9:22C4C00:6A052A36"},"id":"9ec19d07-5a84-4d11-a8e6-e7470533bbee","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:49:54.425Z","parentId":"ab755c1c-74a9-448e-afa2-2c2f6f98668b"}
